<Layout title="Xavier Yin">
	<h1>Xavier Yin</h1>
	<p>
		I'm a PhD student at the <a href="https://www.lti.cs.cmu.edu/">Language
		Technologies Institute</a> at Carnegie Mellon University, advised by
		<a href="https://carlosbusso.com/">Carlos Busso</a> and a member of the
		<a href="https://lab-msp.com/">MSP Lab</a>. I currently work on speech
		articulatory synthesis, particularly text-to-articulation. I've also
		worked on fairness and privacy in large language models &mdash;
		including linguistic bias, standard language ideology, and data privacy
		risks. Before CMU, I completed my M.S. at UC Berkeley, where I worked
		with <a href="https://people.eecs.berkeley.edu/~gopala/">Gopala
		Anumanchipalli</a>; my thesis demonstrated the feasibility of
		text-to-articulation.
	</p>
	<p>
		You can find my research on the <a href="/research">Research</a> page,
		and occasional writing on the <a href="/blog">Blog</a>.
	</p>
</Layout>
